CHAPTER FIVE CONTAINING A FULL ACCOUNT OF THE INSTALLATION OF MR PECKSNIFF'S NEW PUPIL INTO THE BOSOM OF MR PECKSNIFF'S FAMILY . 
He was always in a manner , going to go , and never going . 
He was a kind of animal who infused into the breasts of strangers a lively sense of hope , and possessed all those who knew him better with a grim despair . 
In what respect , having these points of character , he might be fairly likened to his master , that good man's slanderers only can explain . 
But it is a melancholy truth , and a deplorable instance of the uncharitableness of the world , that they made the comparison . 
