'Impossible to say , cried Mr Pecksniff . 
'Giddy truants ! They may be away from home , perhaps . 
Truly Mr Pecksniff is blessed in his children in one of them , at any rate . 
The very onions dangling from the beam , mantle and shine like cherubs' cheeks . 
Something of the influence of those vegetables sinks into Mr Pecksniff's nature . 
'That , indeed , is not such hospitality as I would show to YOU , my friend , cried Mr Pecksniff , pressing his hand . 
And then he took a long breath , and tapping at the window , shouted with stentorian blandness 'Boh ! Cherry dropped her pen and screamed . 
But innocence is ever bold , or should be . 
Mr Pecksniff held out his arms . 
She knew him instantly , and rushed into his fond embrace . 
'It was thoughtless of us , Mr Jonas , it was very thoughtless , said Pecksniff , smoothing his daugther's hair . 
'My darling , do you see that I am not alone ! Not she . 
She had seen nothing but her father until now . 
She saw Mr Jonas now , though and blushed , and hung her head down , as she gave him welcome . 
But where was Merry ? Mr Pecksniff didn't ask the question in reproach , but in a vein of mildness touched with a gentle sorrow . 
She was upstairs , reading on the parlour couch . 
Ah ! Domestic details had no charms for HER . 
'But call her down , said Mr Pecksniff , with a placid resignation . 
'Call her down , my love . 
She was called and came , all flushed and tumbled from reposing on the sofa but none the worse for that . 
No , not at all . 
Rather the better , if anything . 
'Oh ! You're a wicked one ! 'There , go along ! retorted Merry , pushing him away . 
